		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Wolfling1">Wolfling1</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Wolfling1">( 1808594 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65483876">		
		on Sunday June 29, 2025 @09:05AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23730478&amp;cid=65483876">#65483876</a>)
		<small><a href="//slashdot.org/~Wolfling1/journal/" title="Wednesday April 27, 2011 @12:07AM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65483876">I use ChatGPT almost daily.  I use it to write short scripts that have very well defined behaviours.  Sure, it makes mistakes, and I have to check its code, but it saves me a heap of time looking up obscure functions.  And it comments its code quite nicely.  Sometimes, the comments are a bit inane, but I've seen so much uncommented code in my life, seeing any comments at all is a breath of fresh air.<br> <br>
I think that the mistake people make is that they assume that if ChatGPT can write a good 10 line function, then it can write a good 1000 line suite of functions.  It cannot.<br> <br>
Its a tool, and it does very well when it is used in the context in which it performs.  The wrong tool will do poorly at any task.<br> <br>
I would estimate that ChatGPT saves me about 5-6 hours a week.  Time that I can spend on my higher skills rather than my grunt code-monkey skills.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65483876">
