			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65483906" name="comment_link_65483906" href="//slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23730478&amp;cid=65483906" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65483906)" >Ai = Cognitive Mirror</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65483906" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65483906); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Totally_Tux">Totally_Tux</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Totally_Tux">( 452763 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65483906"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65483906"><p>What I find current LLMs the most useful at is to review my work to give a different and useful perspective.</p><p>The LLM doesn't generate any work that goes into my output, it augments my own work to make it better, while I determine what to use (I am in the drivers seat).</p><p>The LLM has been trained in a huge quantity of good quality human-generated text and it surprises me how good it can be at offering associations that I had not considered.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65483906">

